CLASS:PUBLIC
DESCRIPTION:AES1: Literary Analysis Methods and Indigenous Literary Studies
 \n\nAssignment Overview\n\nThis assignment serves two main purposes:\n\nSk
 ill Development: Practice locating\, using\, and discussing textual eviden
 ce (i.e.\, quotations) to support an argumentative interpretation.\n\nUnde
 rstanding Check: Demonstrate your understanding of:\n\n*\n\n*\n\n* Daniel 
 Heath Justice’s essay “Stories that Wound\, Stories that Heal”\n\n* 
 Sherman Alexie’s short story “This is What it Means to Say Phoenix\, A
 rizona”\n\n* Linda Hogan’s poem “The Truth Is”\n\nLiterary Concept
 s to Know\n\nYou’ll need to be familiar with the following literary conc
 epts for both fiction and poetry:\n\n* Plot\n\n* Narration\n\n* Character 
 (for fiction) / Speaker (for poetry)\n\n* Symbol\n\n* Figurative Language 
 / Figures of Speech\n\n* Theme\n\nEach of these areas is covered in the re
 ading packets for this unit\, so refer back to them while you complete the
  assignment.\n\nTexts to Engage With\n\n* Daniel Heath Justice’s “Stor
 ies that Wound\, Stories that Heal”\n\n* Sherman Alexie’s “This is W
 hat it Means to Say Phoenix\, Arizona”\n\n* Linda Hogan’s “The Truth
  Is”\n\nUse your Perusall discussions and notes/comments to help guide y
 our analysis and interpretation.\n\nAssignment Scenario & Format\n\nImagin
 e you are part of a study group. Your role is to organize main ideas from 
 the assigned texts\, link them\, and discuss possible arguments you could 
 make using “Stories that Wound\, Stories that Heal” as a “lens” to
  look at “This is What it Means to Say Phoenix\, Arizona” and “The T
 ruth Is.”\n\nTo accomplish these goals\, you’ll use a What / Where / H
 ow structure to organize your ideas:\n\nWhat? – What is the main idea or
  theme?\n\nWhere? – Where in the text is this idea shown? (Use direct qu
 otations.)\n\nHow? – How does the quote support your interpretation? (Ex
 plain using relevant parts of the quote.)\n\nYou’ll represent these conn
 ections using the table in the provided template (linked at the end of the
  assignment).\n\nTemplate Access\n\nRefer to the linked Excel sheet for th
 is assignment\, which you can download by clicking here: [AES1_Template.do
 cx] (https://canvas.uncp.edu/courses/38584/files/6949244?wrap=1) . This
  template includes columns for each category and is designed to help you c
 learly organize your analysis. You should type your answers directly into 
 the cells on the Excel sheet\, then upload the completed version here as y
 our submission.\n\nThis assignment is designed to help you build foundatio
 nal skills in literary analysis while also giving you a chance to demonstr
 ate your understanding of key texts and concepts. By practicing how to ide
 ntify and interpret textual evidence\, and by making meaningful connection
 s across different genres and voices\, you’re preparing for more complex
  analytical work later in the course. The format is intentionally straight
 forward to keep the focus on your ideas and your ability to support them w
 ith evidence. If you have any questions or concerns as you prepare this as
 signment\, please email me: [zachary.laminack@uncp.edu] (mailto:zachary.la
 minack@uncp.edu). 
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:AES1: Literary Analysis Methods and Indigenous Literary Studies (W1
 &2) [ENG-2200-001-S26]
URL;VALUE=URI:https://canvas.uncp.edu/calendar?include_contexts=course_3858
 4&month=02&year=2026#assignment_943238
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><span style="color: #0e68b3\; font-size: 18
 pt\;"><strong>AES1: </strong></span><span style="color: #0e68b3\; font-siz
 e: 18pt\;"><strong>Literary Analysis Methods and Indigenous Literary Studi
 es</strong></span></p>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Assignment Overview</strong></p>\
 n<p>This assignment serves two main purposes:</p>\n<p style="padding-left:
  40px\;"><strong>Skill Development:</strong> Practice locating\, using\, a
 nd discussing textual evidence (i.e.\, quotations) to support an argumenta
 tive interpretation.</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 40px\;"><strong>Understa
 nding Check:</strong> Demonstrate your understanding of:</p>\n<ul>\n<li st
 yle="list-style-type: none\;">\n<ul>\n<li style="list-style-type: none\;">
 \n<ul>\n<li>Daniel Heath Justice’s essay “Stories that Wound\, Stories
  that Heal”</li>\n<li>Sherman Alexie’s short story “This is What it 
 Means to Say Phoenix\, Arizona”</li>\n<li>Linda Hogan’s poem “The Tr
 uth Is”</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Litera
 ry Concepts to Know</strong></p>\n<p>You’ll need to be familiar with the
  following literary concepts for both fiction and poetry:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>P
 lot</li>\n<li>Narration</li>\n<li>Character (for fiction) / Speaker (for p
 oetry)</li>\n<li>Symbol</li>\n<li>Figurative Language / Figures of Speech<
 /li>\n<li>Theme</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Each of these areas is covered in the read
 ing packets for this unit\, so refer back to them while you complete the a
 ssignment.</p>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Texts to Engage With</strong></p>\n<ul>\n
 <li>Daniel Heath Justice’s “Stories that Wound\, Stories that Heal”<
 /li>\n<li>Sherman Alexie’s “This is What it Means to Say Phoenix\, Ari
 zona”</li>\n<li>Linda Hogan’s “The Truth Is”</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Use y
 our Perusall discussions and notes/comments to help guide your analysis an
 d interpretation.</p>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Assignment Scenario &amp\; Format<
 /strong></p>\n<p>Imagine you are part of a study group. Your role is to or
 ganize main ideas from the assigned texts\, link them\, and discuss possib
 le arguments you could make using “Stories that Wound\, Stories that Hea
 l” as a “lens” to look at “This is What it Means to Say Phoenix\, 
 Arizona” and “The Truth Is.”</p>\n<p>To accomplish these goals\, you
 ’ll use a What / Where / How structure to organize your ideas:</p>\n<p s
 tyle="padding-left: 40px\;"><strong>What?</strong> – What is the main id
 ea or theme?</p>\n<p style="padding-left: 40px\;"><strong>Where?</strong> 
 – Where in the text is this idea shown? (Use direct quotations.)</p>\n<p
  style="padding-left: 40px\;"><strong>How?</strong> – How does the quote
  support your interpretation? (Explain using relevant parts of the quote.)
 </p>\n<p>You’ll represent these connections using the table in the provi
 ded template (linked at the end of the assignment).</p>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>
 Template Access</strong></p>\n<p>Refer to the linked Excel sheet for this 
 assignment\, which you can download by clicking here: <a class="instructur
 e_file_link instructure_scribd_file inline_disabled" title="AES1_Template.
 docx" href="https://canvas.uncp.edu/courses/38584/files/6949244?wrap=1" ta
 rget="_blank" data-api-endpoint="https://canvas.uncp.edu/api/v1/courses/38
 584/files/6949244" data-api-returntype="File">AES1_Template.docx</a> . 
 This template includes columns for each category and is designed to help y
 ou clearly organize your analysis. You should type your answers directly i
 nto the cells on the Excel sheet\, then upload the completed version here 
 as your submission.</p>\n<hr>\n<p><span style="font-size: 10pt\;"><strong>
 This assignment</strong> is designed to help you build foundational skills
  in literary analysis while also giving you a chance to demonstrate your u
 nderstanding of key texts and concepts. By practicing how to identify and 
 interpret textual evidence\, and by making meaningful connections across d
 ifferent genres and voices\, you’re preparing for more complex analytica
 l work later in the course. The format is intentionally straightforward to
  keep the focus on your ideas and your ability to support them with eviden
 ce. If you have any questions or concerns as you prepare this assignment\,
  please email me: <a href="mailto:zachary.laminack@uncp.edu" target="_blan
 k">zachary.laminack@uncp.edu</a>.&nbsp\;</span></p>
END:VEVENT
