DESCRIPTION:You’ll build a small Python tool to measure key network perf
 ormance metrics—latency (ping)\, download throughput\, and upload thro
 ughput—and log them over time. This connects directly to core networking
  ideas: how bandwidth differs from throughput\, why latency and jitt
 er shape user experience\, and how conditions like Wi-Fi vs. wired\, co
 ngestion/peak hours\, routing distance (server selection)\, and protocol
 /ISP policies affect measured performance. By collecting multiple measure
 ments across different times and contexts\, you’ll practice measurement
  methodology (repeat trials\, consistent conditions) and interpret result
 s using concepts from the course (e.g.\, queueing delay\, last-mile constr
 aints\, and path diversity).\n\nIn Short: You’ll create a small Python 
 app that measures your network download speed\, upload speed\, and late
 ncy (ping). You’ll practice working with third-party libraries and basi
 c data visualization. You may turn in the screenshot of your App/Running 
 Program or simply the link of your Jupyter Notebook/Python Scripts\; the 
 format is not that important.\n\nYou may follow any tutorial(s) you would 
 like to follow.\n\nReferences:\n\nhttps://codecapers.com.au/automated-inte
 rnet-speed-testing/\n\nhttps://opensource.com/article/20/1/internet-speed-
 tests\n\nhttps://python.plainenglish.io/internet-speed-tester-using-python
 -d36ec9da7021\n\nhttps://ayushi7rawat.medium.com/internet-speed-test-using
 -python-15b8f2e6bbef\n\nhttps://github.com/openspeedtest/Speed-Test\n\nhtt
 ps://github.com/sivel/speedtest-cli?tab=readme-ov-file#inconsistency\n\nVi
 deos:\n\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k_Ip_uRKvm4\n\nhttps://www.youtub
 e.com/watch?v=cpFGz84FbUc\n\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iM2Ylk1CQ20\n
 \nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DqWIYX_ynQg\n\netc.\n\nMy Sample:\n\n[im
 age.png] (https://canvas.uncp.edu/courses/39731/files/6968727/preview)
