CLASS:PUBLIC
DESCRIPTION:You’ll build a small Python tool to set\, send\, update\, and
  delete HTTP cookies\, and observe how cookies affect session state and us
 er identity on the Web. This connects directly to core networking/web idea
 s: how HTTP is stateless by default\, how cookies create stateful sessions
 \, why cookies matter for authentication\, personalization\, and tracking\
 , and how cookie attributes (Domain\, Path\, Expires/Max-Age\, Secure\, Ht
 tpOnly\, SameSite) affect browser behavior and security. By testing cookie
 s in different scenarios (same site vs cross-site requests\, HTTP vs HTTPS
  simulation\, expiring vs persistent cookies)\, you’ll also practice bas
 ic measurement/debugging methodology: capturing request/response headers\,
  checking cookie jars\, repeating tests\, and explaining results using con
 cepts from the course (HTTP request/response\, headers\, status codes\, se
 ssions\, and common web security concerns like CSRF).\n\nIn Short:\nYou’
 ll create a small Python app that can store cookies locally\, send cookies
  in requests\, and manage cookie lifecycle (create/update/delete/expire). 
 You’ll practice working with third-party libraries and basic debugging t
 ools (printing headers\, logging). You may turn in screenshots of your run
 ning program or simply a link to your Jupyter Notebook / Python script!\n\
 nYou may use the videos as your implementation guide:\n\n* https://www.you
 tube.com/watch?v=enBmKr4gI08\n\n* https://youtu.be/o0UDBlo5tOM\n\nPlease a
 lso go through the article "Python Falcon - Cookies" - https://www.geeksf
 orgeeks.org/python/python-falcon-cookies/\n\nDeliverables Example:\n\n[截
 屏2026-02-19 19.20.51.png] (https://canvas.uncp.edu/courses/39731/files/7
 009615/preview)[截屏2026-02-19 19.21.08.png] (https://canvas.uncp.edu/co
 urses/39731/files/7009616/preview)
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Set and Manage Cookies via Python [CSC-3360-001-S26]
URL;VALUE=URI:https://canvas.uncp.edu/calendar?include_contexts=course_3973
 1&month=02&year=2026#assignment_954919
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>You’ll build a small Python tool to set\,
  send\, update\, and delete HTTP cookies\, and observe how cookies affect 
 session state and user identity on the Web. This connects directly to core
  networking/web ideas: how HTTP is stateless by default\, how cookies crea
 te stateful sessions\, why cookies matter for authentication\, personaliza
 tion\, and tracking\, and how cookie attributes (Domain\, Path\, Expires/M
 ax-Age\, Secure\, HttpOnly\, SameSite) affect browser behavior and securit
 y. By testing cookies in different scenarios (same site vs cross-site requ
 ests\, HTTP vs HTTPS simulation\, expiring vs persistent cookies)\, you’
 ll also practice basic measurement/debugging methodology: capturing reques
 t/response headers\, checking cookie jars\, repeating tests\, and explaini
 ng results using concepts from the course (HTTP request/response\, headers
 \, status codes\, sessions\, and common web security concerns like CSRF).<
 /p>\n<p><span style="text-decoration: underline\;">In Short:</span><br>You
 ’ll create a small Python app that can store cookies locally\, send cook
 ies in requests\, and manage cookie lifecycle (create/update/delete/expire
 ). You’ll practice working with third-party libraries and basic debuggin
 g tools (printing headers\, logging). <strong>You may turn in screenshots 
 of your running program or simply a link to your Jupyter Notebook / Python
  script!</strong></p>\n<p><strong>You may use the videos as your implement
 ation guide:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watc
 h?v=enBmKr4gI08" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=enBmKr4gI
 08</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://youtu.be/o0UDBlo5tOM" target="_blank">ht
 tps://youtu.be/o0UDBlo5tOM</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>Please also go through the 
 article "Python Falcon - Cookies" -&nbsp\;<a href="https://www.geeksforgee
 ks.org/python/python-falcon-cookies/" target="_blank">https://www.geeksfor
 geeks.org/python/python-falcon-cookies/</a></p>\n<p>Deliverables Example:<
 /p>\n<p><img src="https://canvas.uncp.edu/courses/39731/files/7009615/prev
 iew" alt="截屏2026-02-19 19.20.51.png" width="270" height="202" loading=
 "lazy" data-api-endpoint="https://canvas.uncp.edu/api/v1/courses/39731/fil
 es/7009615" data-api-returntype="File"><img src="https://canvas.uncp.edu/c
 ourses/39731/files/7009616/preview" alt="截屏2026-02-19 19.21.08.png" wi
 dth="262" height="203" loading="lazy" data-api-endpoint="https://canvas.un
 cp.edu/api/v1/courses/39731/files/7009616" data-api-returntype="File"></p>
